## Angular 2026 Core Rules for AEM Projects

### TypeScript Best Practices
- Use strict type checking in `tsconfig.json`.
- Prefer type inference when the type is obvious. Avoid explicit typing where unnecessary.
- Never use `any`. Use `unknown` when the type is uncertain, then narrow it with type guards.

### Angular Architecture (v20+)
- Default is standalone. Never set `standalone: true` in decorators — it is the default in Angular v20+.
- Do not use `@HostBinding` or `@HostListener` decorators. Define host bindings in the `host` property of `@Component` or `@Directive` decorator metadata.
- Use `NgOptimizedImage` for all static image URLs. It does not work with inline base64 images — for base64, fallback to standard `[src]` binding.

### Component Design
- Set `changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush` in every `@Component` decorator.
- Use `input()`, `output()`, `model()`, and `viewChild()` signal-based functions. Never use their decorator equivalents (`@Input`, `@Output`, `@ViewChild`).
- Use `computed()` for all derived state. Never recompute values in templates or getter methods.
- Prefer inline templates for components with < 20 lines of HTML. For external templates, always use paths relative to the component TypeScript file.
- Never use `ngClass` or `ngStyle` directives. Use `[class]` and `[style]` bindings instead.
- Components must be small and focused on a single responsibility.

### State Management
- Use Angular `signal()` for all local component state.
- Use `computed()` for derived synchronous state.
- Never call `mutate()` on signals. Use `update()` or `set()` instead to ensure immutability.
- Keep state transformations pure — no side effects inside computed signals.
- For cross-component shared state, prefer services with `signal()` + `computed()` over third-party state libraries unless project scale demands it.

### Templates
- Use only Angular built-in control flow: `@if`, `@else if`, `@else`, `@for`, `@empty`, `@switch`, `@case`, `@default`.
- Never use legacy structural directives: `*ngIf`, `*ngFor`, `*ngSwitch`.
- Use `@let` for template-local variable declarations (available in Angular v18+).
- Keep templates logic-free: move complex logic to component class properties or computed signals.
- Use the `async` pipe for observable subscriptions. Never manually subscribe in components.
- Do not assume browser globals like `window`, `document`, `navigator`, `new Date()` are available in templates. Pre-compute such values in the component class.

### Services & Dependency Injection
- Use the `inject()` function exclusively for dependency injection. Never use constructor injection.
- Design services around a single responsibility.
- Use `providedIn: 'root'` for singleton services unless a specific provider scope is needed.
- Services must expose reactive state via signals or observables.

### Reactive Forms
- Always use Reactive Forms (`ReactiveFormsModule`). Never use Template-driven Forms.
- Form models must be typed using `FormControl<T>`, `FormGroup<T>`, `FormArray<T>`.
- Use `[formControl]` binding for individual controls when possible.

### Routing & Lazy Loading
- Implement lazy loading for all feature routes using `loadComponent` or `loadChildren`.
- Default to `loadComponent` for leaf routes pointing to standalone components.

### AEM SPA Editor Integration Rules
- Components rendered inside AEM containers must be designed to work with AEM's SPA Editor lifecycle.
- Export a mappable component class from every AEM-mapped component using standard AEM SPA Model Manager conventions.
- AEM-mapped components must accept properties via a typed model interface matching the Sling Model exported from AEM.
- Use the `MapTo` function from `@adobe/aem-spa-page-model-manager` to register components.
- Keep AEM-specific logic isolated within dedicated services. Do not spread AEM API calls across components.
- Ensure all AEM-mapped components handle authoring state gracefully (show placeholders when content is empty in Edit mode).

### Accessibility (MANDATORY)
- All components MUST pass AXE accessibility checks.
- Must meet WCAG 2.2 Level AA at minimum.
- Ensure proper focus management, especially after route changes and dynamic content updates.
- Color contrast ratios must meet AA standards (4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text).
- Use semantic HTML and appropriate ARIA attributes.
- Test with keyboard navigation: all interactive elements must be reachable and operable.

